{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"795"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/795"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.26,0.51,0.11,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67930"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"2597"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67930"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with several months of increasing dysphagia and weight loss. He is still able to eat a soft diet but finds that pieces of meat may get stuck. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medication. On physical examination he appears well, with vital signs within normal limits and no abnormalities found on physical examination. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations with endoscopy, CT and PET scans confirm the diagnosis of a 3cm adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus, located in the lower thoracic region. The disease is staged as T2 N0 M0.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatment modalities would be the most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stent insertion","Surgery","Neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy followed by resection","Perioperative chemotherapy and surgery","Resection and adjuvant gefitinib"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for oesophageal cancer is generally based on the stage of the cancer as well as the patient\u2019s comorbid conditions and hence their suitability for surgery. \u003Cstrong\u003ENeoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy followed by resection\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard of care for otherwise fit individuals who have potentially curable carcinoma of the oesophagus. T2N0M0 stage in this case means that the tumour has invaded to the muscularis propria layer of the oesophagus but there is no spread to any lymph nodes or metastases. At this stage neoadjuvant chemoradiation if often used before surgical resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the tumour was small \u0026lt;2cm \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical removal \u003C/strong\u003Ealone may be used, but in this case the tumour is 3cm in size so neoadjuvant therapy is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, the location can change the treatment offered. If the cancer is located at the gastroesophageal junction, then it may be treated with pure \u003Cstrong\u003Echemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E (without the radiation) \u003Cstrong\u003Ebefore proceeding to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case it is in the lower thoracic region but not located at the gastroesophageal junction. Hence, perioperative chemotherapy and surgery would not be recommended in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are active treatment options available to this man, hence \u003Cstrong\u003Ea stent insertion\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate option, unless the patient decided that they did not want any active treatment or surgical resection. A stent would be reserved for patients who had intolerable dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGefitinib \u003C/strong\u003Eis a medication that inhibits the activity of numerous tyrosine kinases including epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR). It is most known for its use in non-small cell lung cancer, but it might have a role in the management of patients with advanced oesophageal cancer, where other first-line therapies have failed. It is still in the trial stage for use in oesophageal cancer but does show some promising results. Hence it would not be an appropriate option for this man as it is not yet approved and he has not failed first line options yet.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early stage oesophageal cancer can be treated with neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy and then proceed to surgery","The options for the treatment of oesophageal cancer depend on the stage and location"],"references":["Ford HE. Gefitinib for oesophageal cancer: a cog in need of a wheel? Lancet Oncol. 2014;15(8):790-1. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/S1470-2045(14)70271-2","Treating Esophageal Cancer by Stage. In: American Cancer Society [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.cancer.org/content/dam/CRC/PDF/Public/8617.00.pdf","Rice TW, Ishwaran H, Blackstone EH. Oesophageal cancer: location, location, location. Eur J Cardiothorac Surg. 2015;48(2):194-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25877947/","Xu Y, Xie Z, Shi Y, Zhang M, Pan J, et al. Gefitinib single drug in treatment of advanced esophageal cancer. J Cancer Res Ther. 2016;12:C295-C297. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/cancerjournal/fulltext/2016/12008/gefitinib_single_drug_in_treatment_of_advanced.19.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"795"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T22:52:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T22:52:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67930"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"